<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="455" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1591,2013]" box="[151,794,1591,1616]" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,794,1591,1616]" fontSize="10" level="2" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" reason="2">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,794,1591,1616]" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">
On 
<taxonomicName authority="Chemsak &amp; Noguera, 1993" authorityName="Chemsak &amp; Noguera" authorityYear="1993" box="[195,794,1591,1616]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Estoloides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scabracaulis">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[195,465,1591,1616]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">Estoloides scabracaulis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Chemsak" box="[472,794,1591,1616]" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" refString="Chemsak, J. A. &amp; Noguera, F. A. (1993) Annotated checklist of the Cerambycidae of the Estacion de Biologia Chamela, Jalisco, Mexico (Coleoptera), with descriptions of a new genera and species. Folia Entomologica Mexicana, 89, 55 - 102." type="journal article" year="1993">Chemsak &amp; Noguera, 1993</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1591,2013]" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">
<bibRefCitation author="Chemsak" box="[199,517,1628,1653]" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" refString="Chemsak, J. A. &amp; Noguera, F. A. (1993) Annotated checklist of the Cerambycidae of the Estacion de Biologia Chamela, Jalisco, Mexico (Coleoptera), with descriptions of a new genera and species. Folia Entomologica Mexicana, 89, 55 - 102." type="journal article" year="1993">Chemsak &amp; Noguera (1993)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chemsak &amp; Noguera" authorityYear="1993" box="[639,813,1628,1653]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Estoloides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scabracaulis">
<emphasis box="[639,813,1628,1653]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">E. scabracaulis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on a large series of males and females, nearly all of which are from Estación de Biologia Chamela (Mexico, Jalisco). According to the authors: “The dense, appressed, pale fulvous pubescence interrupted by glabrous punctures make this species easily recognizable. It is also distinctive by the asperate antennal scape and obtuse lateral tubercles of the pronotum.”
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="456" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1591,2013]" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">
<bibRefCitation author="Martins" box="[199,490,1772,1797]" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" refString="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M. (2010) Novas especies, nova sinonimia e novo registro em Cerambycidae (Coleoptera) do Mexico e da America do Sul. Papeis Avulsos de Zoologia, 50 (7), 83 - 90. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / S 0031 - 10492010000700001" type="journal article" year="2010">Martins &amp; Galileo (2010)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martins &amp; Galileo" authorityYear="2010" box="[614,755,1773,1796]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Estoloides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aurantius">
<emphasis box="[614,755,1773,1796]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">E. aurantius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on a single female from Quintana Roo, and recorded (translated): “ 
<taxonomicName authority="Santos-Silva &amp; Wappes &amp; Galileo, 2018" authorityName="Santos-Silva &amp; Wappes &amp; Galileo" authorityYear="2018" box="[310,601,1807,1832]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Estoloides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aurantius" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Estoloides">
<emphasis box="[310,427,1807,1832]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">Estoloides</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[448,473,1809,1832]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">E.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[494,601,1809,1832]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">aurantius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[613,708,1807,1832]" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[613,708,1807,1832]" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is characterized by the following features: dorsal pubescence orangish, interspersed with contrasting and abundant black punctures; scape with roughness at outer side of apex, and scutellum covered with white pubescence.” Comparison of original descriptions, photographs of the types (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Bezark" box="[151,302,1916,1941]" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" refString="Bezark, L. G. (2017) A photographic Catalog of the Cerambycidae of the New World. Available from: https: // apps 2. cdfa. ca. gov / publicApps / plant / bycidDB / wsearch. asp? w = n (accessed 20 March 2017)" type="journal article" year="2017">Bezark 2017</bibRefCitation>
), and specimens in the MZSP collection (
<figureCitation box="[806,939,1916,1941]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–21. 13" captionStartId="35.[151,264,1932,1955]" captionTargetBox="[193,1406,196,1909]" captionTargetId="figure@35.[185,1408,193,1918]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURES 13–21. 13, Estoloides alboscutellaris, holotype female, dorsal habitus.14, E. annulicornis, holotype female, dorsal habitus. 15, E. reflexa, holotype, dorsal habitus. 16–18, E. prolongata, syntype: 16, lateral habitus; 17, labels, 18, dorsal habitus.19–20, E.scabracaulis, dorsal habitus:19, male; 20, female.21, E.chamelae, male, dorsal habitus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1160910/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">Figs 19–20</figureCitation>
) clearly indicate that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Santos-Silva &amp; Wappes &amp; Galileo" authorityYear="2018" box="[1203,1346,1917,1940]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Estoloides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aurantius">
<emphasis box="[1203,1346,1917,1940]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">E. aurantius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chemsak &amp; Noguera" authorityYear="1993" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Estoloides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scabracaulis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">E. scabracaulis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are synonymous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1591,2013]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1437,151,213]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="456" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">
Two remarkable features make 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chemsak &amp; Noguera" authorityYear="1993" box="[553,727,1988,2013]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Estoloides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scabracaulis">
<emphasis box="[553,727,1988,2013]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">E. scabracaulis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
one of the easiest 
<taxonomicName box="[936,1052,1988,2013]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Estoloides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="455" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[936,1052,1988,2013]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="455">Estoloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species to recognize, these being: the protarsi in male large, with long lateral setae (resembling many species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. Thomson" authorityYear="1860" box="[1031,1196,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Acanthoderini">Acanthoderini</taxonomicName>
), and small asperities near apex, on outer side of scape, in both sexes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
